</example>

      <para id="id2261232">As another example, we take the sum of twenty one iid simple random variables with
integer values. We examine only part of the distribution function where most of the
probability is concentrated. This effectively enlarges the x-scale, so that the
nature of the approximation is more readily apparent.</para>

<example id="fs-id3536095"><title>Sum of twenty-one iid random variables</title><code id="id2261248" display="block">X = [0 1 3 5 6];
PX = 0.1*[1 2 3 2 2];
EX = dot(X,PX)
EX =  3.3000
VX = dot(X.^2,PX) - EX^2
VX =  4.2100
[x,px] = diidsum(X,PX,21);
F = cumsum(px);
FG = gaussian(21*EX,21*VX,x);
stairs(40:90,F(40:90))
hold on
plot(40:90,FG(40:90))
% Plotting details               (see <link target-id="uid3"/>)
</code>
